<SubSection title = "Principles of stability" id = "principles_of_stability">
    
       <Slideshow id = "capsizing_ship_fig">
        <Image alt = "Stability of ship 1" src = "/dyn/the_capsizing_ship/Stability_of_ship_1.png" width = 5></Image>

        <Image alt = "Stability of ship 2" src = "/dyn/the_capsizing_ship/Stability_of_ship_2.png" width = 5></Image>
        
        <Image alt = "Stability of ship 3" src = "/dyn/the_capsizing_ship/Stability_of_ship_3.png" width = 5></Image>
        
    </Slideshow>
    <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic;">
        Image credit: National Transportation Safety Board
    </p>

    <p>
    Ship stability reflects the relationship between buoyancy (the force pushing up on the ships center of buoyancy, <InlineEquation equation="B" />) 
    and gravity (the force pushing down on the ships center of gravity, <InlineEquation equation="G" />). 
    When a vessel is floating upright, the force of gravity and buoyancy are vertically aligned. 
    Vessel stability is usually expressed as the heeling (tilting) moment magnitude necessary to capsize the 
    ship at a specified heeling angle.
    </p>

<p>
    When a disturbing force, such as waves or wind, exerts an inclining moment on a ship, 
    the ship's underwater volume shifts, causing the center of buoyancy to move.
    A ship's metacenter (<InlineEquation equation="M" />) is the virtual intersection between the lines from (1) the original center of buoyancy and (2) 
    the new, heeling center of buoyancy. The distance from a ship's center of gravity to its metacenter is known as the 
    metacentric height (<InlineEquation equation="GM" />), and is used to determine stability. A negative value indicates instability. 
    </p>


    <p>
    Unless the ballast is allowed to change, the center of gravity remains the same, causing the two force directions to become unalligned, 
    risking this negative <InlineEquation equation="GM" /> value. If ballast allows the restoring moment exertion to bring the ship to an even keel, 
    the <InlineEquation equation="GM" /> is positive and the moment is
    known as the righting moment arm. 
    </p>

    

    


